'''Arnfinn Moland''' (born 25 August 1951) is a [[Norway|Norwegian]] historian.

He was born in [[Kvinesdal]]. He finished his secondary education in [[Flekkefjord]] in 1970, served in [[Hans Majestet Kongens Garde|His Majesty the King's Guard]] from 1973 to 1974, and graduated from the [[University of Oslo]] with the [[cand.philol.]] degree in 1977.<ref name=ntb>{{cite news|title=Arnfinn Moland 50 år 25. august|agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]]|date=3 August 2001|language=Norwegian}}</ref> His master's thesis was ''Prissubsider eller støtte? Striden om melkeparagrafen 1972''.<ref>[http://ask.bibsys.no/ask/action/show?pid=010351116&kid=biblio Entry] for ''Prissubsider eller støtte?'' in [[BIBSYS]]</ref> From 1977 to 1978 he took a pedagogical education.<ref name=ntb/> He was also active in athletics. Representing [[Kvinesdal IL]], he achieved a [[long jump]] of 6.91 metres in July 1978 at [[Lovisenlund]] in [[Larvik]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.friidrett.no/friidrett/statistikk/at/sen/MLJ.htm |title=Norwegian all-time list, men's long jump |publisher=Norwegian Athletics |language=Norwegian |accessdate=1 April 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080205231614/http://www.friidrett.no/friidrett/statistikk/at/sen/MLJ.htm |archivedate=February 5, 2008 }}</ref> He had 14.34 metres in the [[triple jump]], achieved in July 1978 at [[Stovnerbanen]] in [[Oslo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.friidrett.no/friidrett/statistikk/at/sen/MTJ.htm |title=Norwegian all-time list, men's triple jump |publisher=Norwegian Athletics |language=Norwegian |accessdate=1 April 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080603033557/http://www.friidrett.no/friidrett/statistikk/at/sen/MTJ.htm |archivedate=June 3, 2008 }}</ref>

Moland was hired as a researcher by [[Norway's Resistance Museum]] in 1978. From 1993 to 1997 he worked for the [[Norwegian Institute for Defence Studies]]. He was the director of Norway's Resistance Museum from 1995, from 1998 with the title of [[associate professor]].<ref name=ntb/>

His first major book was ''Hjemmefront'', volume six of the series ''Norge i krig''. The volume was released in 1987 together with [[Ivar Kraglund]]. In 1997 he released ''"Strengt hemmelig". Norsk etterretningsteneste 1945-1970'', about Norwegian intelligence, together with [[Olav Riste]]. In the same year he released ''Milorg i Stor-Oslo. Distrikt 13s historie'' together with Terje Diesen, about the Greater Oslo district of [[Milorg]]. In 1999 followed ''Over grensen? Hjemmefrontens likvidasjoner under den tyske okkupasjonen av Norge 1940-1945'' about Norwegian liquidations of Nazi collaborators.<ref name=ntb/><ref name=publ>[http://ask.bibsys.no/ask/action/show?pid=010351116&kid=biblio List of publications] in [[BIBSYS]]</ref> This book has been described as a contrast to [[Egil Ulateig]]'s book ''Med rett til å drepe''.<ref name=dagbl2000>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/kultur/2000/11/25/229756.html|title=NS-avkom i norske aviser|last=Mikalsen|first=Espen H.|author2=Aas Olsen, Trygve|date=25 November 2000|work=[[Dagbladet]]|language=Norwegian|accessdate=1 April 2010}}</ref>

He also contributed to film. He was a screenwriter and co-director of the film ''Rapport fra "Nr. 24"'' about [[Gunnar Sønsteby]].<ref name=ntb/> The book ''Gunnar Sønsteby. 24 kapitler i Kjakans liv'' followed in 2004.<ref name=publ/> In 2008 Moland published the book ''Max Manus. Film og virkelighet'', which followed the release of the film ''[[Max Manus (film)|Max Manus]]''. Exploring the relationship between the film and the real-life [[Max Manus]], the book was written together with the film's screenwriter [[Thomas Nordseth-Tiller]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Torp-Holte |first=Torill |year=2009 |title=Tikken versus Max |journal=[[Prosa]] |volume=15 |issue=3 |language=Norwegian |url=http://www.prosa.no/artikkel.asp?ID=479 |accessdate=1 April 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101108212736/http://www.prosa.no/artikkel.asp?ID=479 |archivedate=8 November 2010 }}</ref>

Moland has not been entirely uncontroversial as a historian. In 2000 he accused Norwegian newspapers of printing untrue stories about the [[Norwegian resistance movement]], because "relatives of [[Nasjonal Samling]] sympathizers" sat as editors in these newspapers. The statement was sharply criticized by editors such as [[Harald Stanghelle]], [[Steinar Hansson]] and [[Gudleiv Forr]].<ref name=dagbl2000/>

