{{Infobox patriarch | name=Athanasius II Baldoyo | image= | patriarch_of=[[Syriac Orthodox Church of Antioch|Syriac Orthodox Patriarch of Antioch and All the East]] | church=[[Syriac Orthodox Church]] | see=[[Antioch]] | enthroned =683 | ended=686 | predecessor =[[Severus II bar Masqeh]] | successor=[[Julian III]] | birth_date = | birth_place =[[Balad, Iraq|Balad]], [[Rashidun Caliphate]] | birth_name = | death_date=686 | death_place= [[Umayyad Caliphate]] | residence = | alma_mater = | other = | footnotes = }} '''Athanasius II Baldoyo''' ([[Syriac language|Syriac]]: ''ܐܬܢܐܣܝܘܣ ܕܬܪܝܢ ܒܠܕܝܐ'', [[Arabic language|Arabic]]: ''اثناسيوس الثاني البلدي''), also known as '''Athanasius of Balad''' and '''Athanasius of Nisibis''', was the [[List of Syriac Patriarchs of Antioch from 512 to 1783|Patriarch of Antioch]], and head of the [[Syriac Orthodox Church]] from 683 until his death in 686.<ref name="Barsoum">Barsoum (2003)</ref>
==Biography== Athanasius was born in the city of Balad in [[Upper Mesopotamia]] and studied sciences, [[Syriac language|Syriac]] and [[Greek language|Greek]], with his friend [[Jacob of Edessa|Jacob]], under the tutelage of [[Severus Sebokht]] at the Monastery of Qinnasrin. He moved to the Monastery of Beth Malke, near Antioch, not the Monastery of Mar Malke in [[Tur Abdin]] as originally believed, and became a monk. Athanasius studied philosophy and translated several Greek theological and philosophical works into Syriac, such as [[Porphyry (philosopher)|Porphyry]]'s ''[[Isagoge]]'' in January 645.<ref name="Barsoum"/>
Athanasius later became a priest and moved to [[Nusaybin|Nisibis]], where he continued to translate Greek texts into Syriac. In 666-667, he translated nine treatises of the ''[[Hexameron]]'' of [[Basil of Caesarea]], as suggested by Matthew, Bishop of Aleppo, and Daniel, Bishop of Edessa. Matthew and Daniel later requested a translation of several letters of [[Severus of Antioch]] into Syriac which was complete in 669, under the pen-name of "Athanasius of Nisibis". Athanasius also translated Severus' ''Second Discourse against Nephalius'', several homilies by [[Gregory of Nazianzus]], and the ''Corpus Areopagiticum'' by [[Pseudo-Dionysius the Areopagite]].<ref name="Barsoum"/>
Athanasius was consecrated patriarch at the end of 683 and issued a ten-page proclamation,<ref name="Barsoum"/> and four canons on Christian conduct with Muslims.<ref>Hartmann & Pennington (2012), p. 249</ref> He condemned the consumption of sacrificial meat, participation in Muslim festivals, and relationships with Muslims.<ref>Hoyland (1997), pp. 148-149</ref> In 684, he ordained his friend [[Jacob of Edessa|Jacob]] as bishop of Edessa. Athanasius also wrote a number of supplication prayers, several of which were to be used at the celebration of the Eucharist, and prayers for the dead. He died at the end of 686.<ref name="Barsoum"/>
