{{About|the [[Japanese era name]] Jōgen occurring during the [[Heian period]]||Jōgen (disambiguation){{!}}Jōgen}}
{{History of Japan|Shoso-in.jpg| Image explanation = [[Shōsōin]]}}

{{nihongo|'''Jōgen'''|貞元|}} was a {{nihongo|[[Japanese era name|Japanese era]]|年号,|''nengō'',|lit. "year name"}} after ''[[Ten'en]]'' and before ''[[Tengen (era)|Tengen]].''  This period spanned the years from July 976 through November 978.<ref>Nussbaum, Louis-Frédéric. (2005). "''Jōgen''" in {{Google books|p2QnPijAEmEC|''Japan Encyclopedia'', p. 429|page=429}}; n.b., Louis-Frédéric is pseudonym of Louis-Frédéric Nussbaum, ''see'' [https://archive.is/20120524174828/http://dispatch.opac.ddb.de/DB=4.1/PPN?PPN=128842709 Deutsche Nationalbibliothek Authority File].</ref> The reigning emperor was {{nihongo|[[Emperor En'yū|En'yū]]''-tennō''|円融天皇}}.<ref>Titsingh, Isaac. (1834). [https://books.google.com/books?id=18oNAAAAIAAJ&pg=PP9&dq=nipon+o+dai+itsi+ran#PRA1-PA144,M1  ''Annales des empereurs du japon'', pp. 144–146;] Brown, Delmer ''et al.'' (1979). ''Gukanshō'', p. 299–300; Varely, H. Paul. (1980). ''Jinnō Shōtōki'', pp. 191–192.</ref>

==Change of era==
* '''February 3, 976''' {{nihongo|''Jōgen gannen''|貞元元年}}<!-- NengoCalc 貞元一年一月一日 -->: The new era name was created to mark an event or a number of events. The previous era ended and a new one commenced in ''Ten'en'' 4, on the 13th day of the 7th month of 976.<ref>Brown, p. 300.</ref>

==Events of the ''Jōgen'' era==
* '''June 11, 976''' (''Jōgen 1, 11th day of the 5th month'')<!-- NengoCalc 貞元一年五月十一日 -->: The Imperial Palace was destroyed by a great fire.<ref name="t145">Titsingh, [https://books.google.com/books?id=18oNAAAAIAAJ&pg=PP9&dq=nipon+o+dai+itsi+ran#PRA1-PA145,M1  p. 145.]</ref>
* '''December 20, 977''' ('Jōgen 2, 8th day of the 11th month'')<!-- NengoCalc 貞元二年十一月八日  -->: [[Fujiwara no Kanemichi]] dies at the age of 51.<ref>Titsingh, [https://books.google.com/books?id=18oNAAAAIAAJ&pg=PP9&dq=nipon+o+dai+itsi+ran#PRA1-PA146,M1  p. 146.]</ref>

